Today is International Day for People With Disabilities! Nine years ago I didn’t know much about people like me. I was busy dancing as a professional ballroom dancer all over the globe, having zero limitations.
In 2013 that all changed because of a senseless act of terrorism. Since then, I’ve helped change laws on capital hill, I’ve raised tens of thousands for amputees to receive legs in the US, Ecuador, and Guatemala. I’ve helped create a new division in the Boston marathon for runners like me. I’ve been relentless in my advocacy because I know that one voice is just one voice, but it can change the world for so many. This jewelry collection reflects what strength and resilience look like. Simple yet powerful, sleek yet strong. My running blade, each cut by hand by the incomparable Erica Sara, co designed by us, for you. For you to remember that we are all resilient, we are all strong, and we all have a home no matter what our bodies look like.
On this International Day for People With Disabilities, I hope you recognize the strength within EVERY BODY as you shop the anklet, necklace, and bracelet. We are ALL Boston Strong 💙💛 LINK IN POST PHOTO AND STORIES!

I don’t know about you, but I loved 2022!! It wasn’t surprising to see your most loved posts, because they were mine, too!! Running the marathon with my dear friend, teammate, coach and mentor Shalane was a dream. The only thing better than the experience for us was knowing we were inspiring others to chase after their big dreams, too.
I had SO many highs this year. Fell in love, ran Boston, stared in a @wbztv commercial, yelled “Play Ball!” on the field at Fenway, threw the first pitch at Fenway, made the cover of the Washington Post, returned to in person speaking events and grew my business tenfold, raced and won the first ever Para Division of the BAA 10k on my 42nd birthday, learned to kayak, launched my clothing line, launched a jewelry line with @ericasara , walked the red carpet at New York Fashion Week, was chased by a helicopter all over the white mountains for my IMAX film, found a new therapist, and a new leg guy, went to a bunch of Celtics games, and spoke to countless companies and groups, and hugged and met so many of YOU in real life!
What a year!! This year also had its share of really tough moments, but it’s nothing I can’t handle. This year I’m SO PUMPED my IMAX movie will finally come out (eeeek!! June!!!) I’ll finalize my book deal (a lifetime in the making!!!) and finally tell my full story, and reflect and remember this April’s marathon weekend is the ten year anniversary of the day I lost my leg.
Today, as I reflect on 2022, and the past ten years, I feel proud of the woman I’ve become and the life I’m living. Since I was in the hospital I knew there would never be an ‘all better’ so I simply wished for more good days than bad days. And I’ve succeeded in that goal. And it is never lost on me that YOU, here on instagram, are a giant reason I keep going. Thank you, endlessly, for your continued support and love. I hope you feel it back tenfold. Love you!!

2023 Race Announcement 💙💛
First of all, can you believe it’s already 2023?! Yeah, me either! 2022 was my best running year yet, between my steady strong buildup and 4th place in the Boston Marathon in April, to winning the @teambaa 10K in June. So many miles, so many smiles!! Since finishing that marathon, I’ve thought ‘that’s it, I’ve peaked, nothing can top that day.’ I mean, I can always be faster, but the amount of child-like elation I had from start to finish could never be duplicated. I’ve gone back and forth about running 2023 ever since. It’s the ten year anniversary of the bombings, which means I both want to run as well as cheer at the same time. Anyone who runs Boston knows that if you are running the marathon, it is very tough to have the bandwidth to do anything else that weekend, both mentally and physically.
I love the Boston Marathon. It’s also a complicated emotional time to recognize something so tough (losing my leg) alongside my most favorite event (the marathon) with my most favorite people on the planet (the BAA and the running community). I wish I had the bandwidth for all of the emotions that come with so much goodness and also the hard.
After talking to my mentors, my therapist, my sponsors, and my family, I’ve decided to not run the marathon, and race to win the @teambaa 5K that Saturday before the marathon. I am eternally grateful the BAA has extended the Para Division to their other races and invited me to race the 5K. THANK YOU!! It also just so happens that the 5K lands on April 15th, the exact anniversary of losing my leg. I will give that race my EVERYTHING as I fly past that sidewalk on the course that morning going for the win. Then I will crack open a @samueladamsbeer (or two) and get ready to stand at the sidelines cheering and screaming and hugging and watching all of YOU become unicorns!!! There is nothing I’d rather do than show you the kind of deep love and support you’ve shown me in this race. Oh, and if you’re free and in town that Saturday morning before the marathon, come cheer the 5k!!! Here’s to a new distance, a brand new division, and a strong training cycle!!!
#bostonstrong

Thought I’d take a minute to re-introduce myself since I have a few new faces around here!
Hi, I’m Adrianne. I travel and share my story to large corporations, schools, organizations, and NGOs. I share life lessons I’ve had to learn and relearn along the way. I lost my leg at the terrorist attack at the Boston marathon bombings in 2013, then was hit by a car in 2019, suffering severe damage to my left side almost losing my left arm. It’s bolted back together and now neither my elbow or my shoulder can rotate. After all that I’ve been through, my life’s mission is to make others feel less alone in their suffering. Whether you are facing a speed bump or Mount Everest, I’m here to tell you it’s ok to cry and feel it all, because that’s the only way through to the other side.
I grew up outside of Seattle, Washington in a little town called Issaquah. It was Microsoft country before it was Microsoft country, and I loved it. I grew up in my parent’s independent books and records store, with different bands, writers and artists staying the night in our home every night. Dinners were spent hearing Eddie Vedder’s life story, or poems by Nikki Grimes. It was pure magic, and the live music memories are endless. It sparked my love of dance, and after high school I skipped college to chase a dream as a professional ballroom dancer. I somehow got the gig and competed and danced for the large part of my career, up until losing my leg. I relearned to dance again after, winning my first competition back. I then traded in one dream for another; running. I no longer wanted to stand in front of crusty old men holding up 1-10 numbers to ‘rate’ my body in a sequined bikini. Running, sweating, and throwing snot rockets is way healthier!!!! I’ve since run in 3 Boston marathons and helped create the new Para Division. I’m not terribly fast but I freaking love it and I try my best, so who cares. I mentor lots of young female amputees through the first year of their new normal. It’s what I needed and never want anyone to feel alone in their suffering. I love therapy and cannot stress enough how much it’s helped me over the years. And I’m a momma to my almost seven year old service dog🐾❤️

Decades ago I thought…wouldn’t it be fun to enroll in a pottery school? I finally asked myself at new years why I hadn’t done it yet, and I couldn’t come up with a reason. Busy? Yes! But so is every adult. I bet they accommodate. I’ll probably suck! But so will everyone in class..it’s beginner! I enrolled within a day.

So here I am, three classes in, messing up, loving every minute of sucking at something new. And I absolutely love it 🥹 a ton of skills learned, and, most importantly, lessons learned. Life lessons I will apply everywhere;

•Don’t compare your beginning to someone else’s middle. You don’t want to be them anyway, right?
•If you think you’ve got it all figured out, you don’t. And that’s effing beautiful.
•Move slowly. No…slower. Breathe. Slower. You’re rushing because you think you should have everything figured out. Silly goose, no one does. Move slow.
•And, the best lesson, from my brother, a ceramics teacher in Cali and life long artist; do not let the irregularities in the clay make YOU move when centering, make the irregularities in the clay clay move with YOU. You will center as a result.

I highly recommend starting a very new hobby/skill (preferably art that doesn’t have rigid rules) as an adult. Grow. Grow grow. Follow my boring slow..no…slower..even slower now, boring messing up journey over at @akhceramics

With the ten year anniversary quickly approaching, I’ll be sharing some of my favorite memories over the next two months, in no particular order. Here is one of my most memorable;

My Superman surgeon stood at the end of my bed, with my discharge papers in hand. He was crying, I was crying. As you can imagine, we had grown incredibly close as we navigated through the unthinkable. (Fun fact; we’re still close, and his daughter is now a ballroom dancer!) Neither one of us wanted me to go back out into the big scary world, where terrorists were, where it was unsafe. He then said to me “Adrianne, in order for me to sign these discharge papers and let you go, you need to make me three promises.” I asked what they were

“Promise number one; do not let anyone else take out your stitches. Book your appointment with me and me only.” I said that’s an easy one, I now have trust issues and you’re stuck with me now.

“Promise number two; Adrianne, when you dance again, not if, you tell me and I’ll be there to cheer you on. Whether that’s in your kitchen, or on a stage, I’ll be there to cheer you on” I said I promise, even though I didn’t believe it would happen.

“Promise number three; Adrianne, when you run the Boston Marathon, not if, you tell me and I will be cheering you on from start to that finish line.” I sobbed and said I promise, as I looked down at my amputated leg, that was swollen beyond recognition, with half my hair burnt off and only one eyebrow left. I didn’t think it would ever be possible.

Ten years later, three promises kept, it’s the lesson I talk about on every stage I’ve spoken; believe in the conviction of others even when you may not believe it yourself. We are all extraordinarily skilled at doubting ourselves, especially when the entire deck is stacked against us. That’s why we need our tribes. I believed because he believed in me. And you, here on instagram, help me still believe in me too. Thank you for helping me through the last ten years. You inspire me beyond words. I can’t make this post without a shoutout to @bostonmedicalcenter for your continued dedication to your people, so people like me can thrive.

With the ten year anniversary quickly approaching, I’ve been sharing memories that have stood out. In no particular order, here is another one that shaped me;

I was hanging in my hospital room, four days after being blown up by that terrorist. I was connected to every tube, wire, and IV out of every hole and crevice of my body. My mom came in, blushing. She said “you’ll never believe who I just met!” Right after, in walked Anderson Cooper and four cameras. I immediately started licking my hands and trying to pat down my hair and my one eyebrow, like a cat.
He sat down and asked if we could talk. I said yes, staring into his kind blue eyes. Halfway through the interview he asked if I’d ever dance again. I said “yeah, I hope so. I don’t know how I’ll do it with one foot but I’m going to try”
He replied “if you learn again, will you teach me?!” I immediately said “heck yeah, absolutely!”
It felt so good to say a goal out loud that I somehow found it in me to say “And I think I’ll run the Boston Marathon too. I want to say thank you to everyone who has shown this Boston Strong movement.”
Anderson said “You have spent the entire interview talking about how you’re not a runner. Do you think you can do that? With one leg?”
I said “I’m going to try. There was a time in my life I wasn’t a ballroom dancer, and I made it to third in the world. So I think I can shoot for this too.”
These moments led to one of the biggest life lessons of all; say your dreams out loud. I was so taken by our conversation that I didn’t remember the cameras were on. But they were, and millions were glued to their TVs.
Those viewers found me, on social, on sidewalks, in restaurants, in random conversations, and you held me accountable. You believed in me. Thank you, for hearing my dreams once and believing I could achieve them days, years, even a decade later. Anderson, you’re a gem and I’m eternally grateful for our conversation which led to our (Emmy nominated!) movie The Survivor Diaries. Your team is a dream and I’m eternally grateful for capturing year one as an amputee.
Follow along for more memories leading up to the ten year anniversary of the Boston Marathon Bombings.
#bostonstrong

I heard a loud blast behind me and the ground shook. I turned to see black smoke in place of the finish line, and people running in every direction. I screamed “the next one is going to hit!” Knowing this was no accident, we were all in trouble. I still don’t know what made me say that. Just as it left my mouth…boom. I was on the ground.
All I saw was grey. It felt like I had a building on top of me, and I couldn’t hear a thing. I wasn’t sure if I was alive or dead. The grey started to clear and I smelled that all too familiar smell when you get your curlers tangled; burnt hair. I immediately flailed my arms and patted flames off of my head.
I could suddenly hear and move - a little. I lifted my head, my shoulders, my right leg. I saw tons of blood pouring from my thigh. I tried to lift my left leg - to no avail. Tried again. I looked. The smoke cleared more. I tried lifting again. And there it was. No left leg. Only the skin flap and toenails
I howled.
I rolled over onto my belly and barrel crawled to a doorway.
I was dragged by a bystander to a stairwell where an off duty doctor applied tourniquets to each leg and kept me alive until five of the hottest Boston firemen came to take me to Boston Medical Center.
BMC would become my cocoon, where I hid and was held safely and tightly until my Superman Surgeon was ready to set me free to fly.
A lot of people know my story. I’ve done a lot of press. Yet I’ve lied in every interview I’ve ever given when asked what makes me so strong, what I thought of first when I went down on that sidewalk.
A tiny handful of humans know the truth.
I was adopted. Some know that.
What you don’t know? My birth mother was killed by a monster just like mine, off of a sidewalk, just like mine.
That story is well known. My relation, because of the closed adoption, is not known to anyone. But because it was a sign of the times, her side was never told. Only the monster’s story was told. That is about to change.
I never got a chance to say thanks. I could never ask if she was proud.

Hey you. Yes, you. You that just ran the Boston Marathon. This one is for those who’s day did not go as planned. I know you’re out there. I see you scrolling. I see you reading race recap after race recap of everyone’s ‘magical’ ‘once in a lifetime’ ‘personal best’ ‘felt good the entire way’ posts. I see you wondering, how on earth did I not have my day? You trained so dang hard. You ached for this race, on this day, in this city. Your friends and loved ones were here. They made signs. They made reservations for the after party. To celebrate you. And you DNFd. Or bonked. I’m here to tell you…I’ve been there. And it’s ok to be paralyzed in heartbreak. You’re watching everyone else celebrating and you don’t feel it. You are aching for this to not be real. Please be a bad dream.
I DNFd in 2018 from hypothermia. I had trained so hard. My parents were at the finish waiting. I had talked a real good game, publicly, and then I couldn’t even get past mile 10. WOOF. I know what you’re feeling. But did I let that feeling bring down my relationship with running and the rest of my existence? SURE DID. It consumed me. I cried for weeks. Of course so many people didn’t finish that year, it was insane conditions. But you couldn’t justify it with me. I was convinced I was a failure. It took a long time to get out of that funk. So, if you’re feeling super down on yourself, and you had a tough day out there, I’m here to tell you… it gets better. But first, you’ve got to acknowledge that it’s ok to have a bad day. We all have bad runs, and sometimes those bad runs happen to fall on actual race day. Remember this; the amount of hurt you feel is directly proportionate to the amount of hope you had. And hope, my friend, is what will get you back up, back out there, and back to Hopkinton again. But first, cry. Do not let that water drown you. I’m so proud you chased that unicorn.

Guess what today is?!? It’s my TEN YEAR WALKAVERSARY!!! Ten years ago today, I took my very first steps. Only 39 days after losing my leg, four months ahead of doctor’s schedule, and bawling the entire way. I wish everyone remembered what it is like to take their very first steps. To learn how to trust a brand new body, stepping on something you cannot feel, and trusting it to hold you. Trusting wet tile after the rain, that your foot won’t slip and you move your body weight and core over it at the precise moment. Trusting a New England winter and ice underfoot. And, above all, trusting stairs.

You place your foot halfway off the stair, begin to move ALL of your body weight forward, then FALL ON THE NEXT STAIR but catch yourself with your next foot. 🤯😱 IT’S FREAKING SCARY! My leg guy tried to order new skin, but it was back ordered until the end of August. 😤 So he tracked down a (much) lighter shade, and it finally came in yesterday. I don’t love the lighter shade, but I’m grateful nonetheless.
I’ll never understand why the porn and film industry spends billions on making durable flexible skin for dolls and robots but the prosthetic industry has so little resources. There are 2.2 million people living with limb loss/limb difference in this country, 508 new amputees every day. People with disabilities are the largest minority in this country. And while not everyone uses/needs skin, there is a giant market for it. Any ideas for a more durable, flexible skin material? I’m having great conversations about this in my direct messages but want to hear from you in comments, so we can bounce ideas off of each other. I hope you learn from me, and I’d love to learn from you, what can be done differently? This skin is out of pocket and I got a discount today but can be $1500.

When I was in school, we had earthquake drills. Every week we’d hear the alarm and dive under our desks so fast that if you blink, you’d miss it. My tiny shaking hands gripped the legs of the desk, and I buried my head between my elbows.
I was an anxious kid. (In what is not not breaking news - I still am) I got as still as a statue. We all knew and heard on the news ‘the big one’ would hit Seattle at some point, and our parents and teachers talked about it often.
We’d wait for the all clear to go back to class as normal. Every so often, it would go off again immediately- preparing us for aftershocks. Again - nose dive! Under the desk. Crayons, stuffed animals would fall to the ground but we didn’t dare reach from our safe space to get them.
Decades later in my therapist’s office I asked him why I felt paralyzed by ptsd, why I couldn’t do even a simple task without feeling danger or at least uneasy. He looked at me and said “Adrianne, you can’t build in an earthquake.” I audibly gasped. He continued “When someone is going through something deeply hard, all you can do is wait it out. You can’t lay a foundation - or even a brick - that will hold. The words you say will shake in your throat, and you’ll cry. And here’s why it’s hard - no one else feels the quake. They’re in a garden. Adrianne, you cannot build right now. You will feel the ground settle eventually. But remember - there will be aftershocks. You’ll know what to do. Get under your desk and wait.”
I had never told him about my earthquake drills. I’d never had anything make more sense in my life than that moment.
Years later I was telling a friend I’d wished I’d taken up a language or knitting when I spent so much time sitting in that hospital bed. Not soon after, I was hit by a car going 40mph, and yet again, in a hospital bed. Breaking news - I didn’t take up a language or knitting. I crawled under my blankets, and I held on tight. I protected that scared little anxious terrified girl inside me. I waited.
••Excerpt from the chapter EARTHQUAKE DRILLS from my book that I hope to finish sooner than later!

It’s my solo walkaversary!! Ten years ago this week, I took my very first unassisted steps! When I walked for the first time, (see post from July 2nd!) I needed a walker, because my couldn’t handle full weight into my leg. I was in a TON of pain with every step. When you shove your leg into your prosthetic, it’s angry. It’s been (clearly) traumatized, and the stitches are fresh, the muscles and bones and nerves are - furious. You step into it, and attempt a first step forward.

I quickly realized how painful it would be - to have those fragile nerves shoot right back up my entire body. I think this was the most surprising part - that it didn’t just snap on like a Lego and I could walk out the door. Quite the opposite. I wore it 5 min a day, then 10, then 20, then hours, then more and more until I got to this point. When I walked across that tiny apartment all by myself without assistance. In the days since, I vividly remember walking my first full block, my first cobblestone street, my first walk in the rain, snow, and on stairs.

Here’s to our little moments. Days where we can barely move forward. But we take tiny, yet huge, steps forward. Remember - those tiny steps can lead to walking the Annapurna Circuit, runway shows, running races, walking from Copley Square to Maine in 7 days, two marathons, and endless possibilities. Yes. Your life can change in a matter of 3.5 seconds. I know mine has, many times. But it is up to you to make every single second count after. Because believe me, they do.

I’m unbelievably grateful I can wear my leg all day every day without ever being in pain, taking it off, or even noticing that it’s on. I’m aware that’s rare but credit my surgeon and leg team. I literally live life like all of you and will work tirelessly until every amputee feels equally as normal as I do!

My DMs have been full of questions regarding therapy - where to go, how it works, will it even help. I never push anyone. But. I can tell you why therapy works and how it works for me.
Remember when you were little, you fell and scraped your knee? You ran - maybe even crying - to your adult wanting them to clean you up and stop the pain. The first thing they did was to reassure you you’re going to be ok - this is emotionally regulating you. Then they poured disinfectant on it to clean it out - and it stung - badly. We usually cried harder but knew it was for the best. The reason being it wouldn’t get infected and spread to the rest of our bodies, further hurting us. Then they put a bandaid on and off we went to face the day. We often went back to change the bandaid and get reassured it was healing correctly.
This is the same as therapy.
We are out in the world and get scraped up. But. Now we’re adults. Our skinned knees are now brutal breakups, traumatizing images, being laid off, a pet passing away, terrorist attacks, and so on. We may run to our adults only to realize they have their own skinned knees and we don’t want to ‘burden’ them. We’re told by society we need to just handle it.
Therapists are our adults. They have a calming voice - regulating our nervous system. They hear our skinned knee stories and they - very gently - pour a little disinfectant on our cuts. It stings. Yes. But here’s why it’s just as important as that skinned knee. It stops the infection spreading to other parts of our lives. Stops us from bleeding on people who never cut us. Physical infections can spread and cost us our lives. So can mental ones. Therapists help clean us out and - before we leave their office, they make sure we’re all bandaged up and feel safe enough to face the world again. Then, when we return, we check the cut to make sure it healing properly. They clean it out again. Each time, we heal. We still scar. But we heal. Head over to my stories to ask me anything about therapy today. I couldn’t do this thing called life without it.
❤️‍🩹Being traumatized is walking through the world with third degree burns. Treat them as such.

Just because it’s yours, doesn’t mean you need to carry it alone.
Have you experienced something so difficult it left a permanent mark on your life? That there is this proverbial before and after that moment? Where it seems like everything changed? Maybe it was a heartbreak, a job loss, losing a loved one or experiencing a traumatic event.
I’m often asked how I live with PTSD. How I cope with such trauma(s) and live a fairly ‘normal’ life.
It may go without saying that some days are easier than others. And yet, some days are downright debilitating. When I experience a forever life changing event, I think of my life as a little girl growing up in the Pacific Northwest. We had earthquake drills. The alarms would sound and we’d duck and cover under our tiny desks, our little arms clutching the legs waiting for it to pass, for an adult to tell us we’re safe, we can come out of hiding. During the drills, the teachers would sometimes shake the desk, causing your pencils, toys, and papers to fly everywhere. All you could do was hold on and wait for it to pass. Just as we’d get back to feeling safe again - the aftershocks came. Under the desks we’d go, waiting. Worrying.
This - is PTSD. Some days, weeks even can be joyous and then BOOM. Out of nowhere - an aftershock. You know what it is and you think you can handle it fine…but your nervous system decides otherwise. Your heart races, your body goes into fight/fawn/freeze or flight and you have zero control. You look around the room for comfort and yet - no one else feels the quake. HOW do they not feel it?! You hide in the bathroom and isolate, try and breathe, push yourself to push through.
If this sounds familiar, you are not alone. Living with aftershocks asks that you learn where your desk is, where you can find safety when you’re the only one feeling the quake.
If learning coping strategies while in community with others who are feeling the same sounds comforting and safe for you, I encourage you to drop me your email at the link in my story. You will be sent information to further decide if this is right for you. My peer to peer group You Strong is for anyone looking to feel less alone. It’s my greatest work.

Four years ago tonight I was walking to dinner. I waited for the cross walk, and walked across the 300 block of Commonwealth Ave. The street that I visited from Seattle at 9 yrs old telling my parents “I’m going to live here one day!” The street that Hemingway called the most beautiful street in America. I walked, on my way to dinner exactly 100 days out from the 2019 Boston marathon I was training for.
Then - a car - without headlights - came out of nowhere and - S L O W motion. I saw the bumper crash into my left leg. My shin. My prosthetic leg. The carbon fiber of my leg was slammed by the carbon fiber of the car’s bumper and I was airborne - I saw the familiar windows of my brownstone spinning in circles and BOOM. I landed. A few car lengths down. Shoulder first. Crunch. I felt my body land on it then get closer to the ground as the bones disintegrated to dust under the weight of me. My legs landed, then my head. My head landed last. That’s the only reason I’m still here.
I screamed a primal ache. I sat up. MY ARM STAYED LAYING ON THE GROUND NEXT TO ME FROM MY COLLAR BONE DOWN. I howled. Neighbors. 911. The man in the car. His face. His face. His unemotional face. The cops telling me he didn’t mean it. The rage. His dead stare. My screams. The same hot firemen who rescued me in 2013. Reassurance. His face that never lost eye contact. Without fear. His face. The EMT calling my Superman Surgeon from the ambulance per my request and holding the phone to my ear. Howling. Screams. Reassurance. The ride to the hospital. My Superman’s face as the doors opened. Being told I’m definitely going to lose my arm. Refusing to sign the papers giving permission to amputate if needed. A few more surgeries. Months in the hospital longer than I ever was in 2013. Now - forever not being able to use that arm the same way at all.
Four years. A tough day. I’ve never spoken about most of that (my coach at the time took it upon himself to speak for me to press without my permission because MEN🙄) it was a real struggle for me. Which leads me to the point of this…thank you for your support. This experience reminds me everyone has unknown anniversaries. I see you. ❤️‍🩹
